To prevent your baby from developing a flat spot, it's important to vary their position frequently. Encourage tummy time while they're awake and supervised, as this helps strengthen neck muscles and reduces pressure on the back of the skull. You can also alternate the direction your baby faces during feeding and playtime to encourage them to turn their head in different directions. Using positioning aids like rolled towels or special pillows designed for infants may help distribute pressure more evenly, though these should be used cautiously and only after consulting with your pediatrician.

