Neonatal hyperbilirubinemia refers to an elevated level of bilirubin in the blood of newborns. Bilirubin is a yellow pigment produced when old red blood cells break down. In most cases, this condition resolves on its own as the baby's liver matures and becomes more efficient at processing bilirunbin. However, if left untreated, high levels of unconjugated (indirect) bilirrubin can cross the blood-brain barrier and cause kernicterus, a type of brain damage that can lead to serious complications such as hearing loss, cerebral palsy, or even death.

The primary symptom of neonatal hyperbilurubinemia is jaundice (yellowing of the skin and whites of the eyes), which typically appears within 24-72 hours after birth. Other signs may include poor feeding, lethargy, irritability, and difficulty waking up for feedings. These symptoms occur because excess biliribin affects the central nervous system.

