There are three main types of federal budgetary actions: regular appropriations bills, continuing resolutions (CRs), and supplemental appropriation bills. 

Regular appropriations bills provide funding for specific government agencies or programs on an annual basis. These bills must be passed by Congress before the start of the fiscal year to ensure that agencies have the necessary funds to operate throughout the year.

A Continuing Resolution (CR) is used when Congress has not yet completed its work on all 12 regular appropriations bills by October 1st, which marks the beginning of the new fiscal year. A CR allows certain parts of the government to continue operating at the previous year's spending levels until more permanent legislation can be enacted. This prevents a shutdown of non-essential services while giving lawmakers additional time to finalize their budgets.

