The Electoral College is a process used to elect the President of the United States. Each state has a certain number of electoral votes based on its representation in Congress (the sum of its Senators and Representatives). When voters cast their ballots for president, they are actually voting for a slate of electors pledged to that candidate. The candidate who wins the majority of electoral votes (at least 270 out of 538) becomes the President. This system was established by the Founding Fathers as a compromise between direct popular vote and selection by Congress.

What happens if no candidate receives a majority of the electoral votes?

If no candidate secures at least 269 electoral votes, the House of Representatives selects the President from among the top three candidates with the most electoral votes. In this scenario, each state delegation gets one vote, regardless of population size. Similarly, the Senate chooses the Vice President from the top two vice-presidential candidates. If neither chamber can reach a decision within six days before inauguration day, the Speaker of the House serves as Acting President until a resolution is reached.

