Remission refers to a state where the signs and symptoms of cancer have decreased or disappeared. It is important to note that remission is not the same as a cure. A cure implies that all traces of cancer have been eliminated and there is no risk of recurrence. In contrast, remission means that while the cancer may be under control, there is still a possibility that it could return.

There are two main categories of remission: partial remission (PR) and complete remission (CR). Partial remission occurs when at least 50% but less than 100% of the tumor has shrunk after treatment. Complete remission, on the other hand, indicates that all detectable evidence of cancer has vanished following therapy. However, even in cases of complete remission, regular follow-up tests are necessary because small amounts of cancer cells might remain undetected.

Furthermore, remission can also be classified based on its duration:
- **Short-term remission**: This type lasts for up to one year.
- **Long-term remission** (also known as durable remission): This persists beyond five years without significant progression
