Structured sparsity extends this concept by considering additional constraints on the structure of the non-zero elements. For example, group sparsity assumes that the non-zero coefficients occur in predefined groups, while tree-structured sparsity considers hierarchical relationships between variables. These structures provide more prior knowledge about the signal, which can lead to better reconstruction performance compared to standard sparsity assumptions.

